'''Trevor Linden''', [[Order of British Columbia|OBC]], (born [[April 11]], [[1970]]) is a [[Canada|Canadian]] professional [[ice hockey]] player. He plays [[Centre (ice hockey)|centre]] and [[Winger (ice hockey)|right wing]] for the [[Vancouver Canucks]] of the [[National Hockey League]] (NHL). Since joining the league in [[1988-89 NHL season|1988]], he has played with four different teams: the Canucks (in two stints), [[New York Islanders]], [[Montreal Canadiens]], and [[Washington Capitals]]. Before joining the NHL, Linden captained the [[Medicine Hat Tigers]] of the [[Western Hockey League]] (WHL) to consecutive [[Memorial Cup]] championships.<ref name="Canuck Legends">{{cite book | last = Rud | first = Jeff  | title = Canucks Legends: Vancouver's Hockey Heroes | year = 2006 | publisher = Raincoast Books | location = Vancouver |id = ISBN 978-1-55192-809-8}}</ref> In addition to appearing in two [[NHL All-Star games]], Linden was a member of the [[1998 Winter Olympics|1998]] [[Ice hockey at the 1998 Winter Olympics|Canadian Olympic team]] and participated in the [[1996 World Cup of Hockey]].

Throughout his career, Linden has been recognized as a  respected leader on and off the ice.<ref name="Pregame Speech">{{cite news |title =Linden's 'huge' pre-game chat lifts spirits|url =http://www.canada.com/theprovince/news/story.html?id=683f3ad4-6060-4637-a7ba-0469a014e15b&k=784|author =Botchford, Jason|publisher =[[The Province]]|date =[[2008-03-16]]|accessdate =2008-03-16}}</ref><ref name="Salvage Lockout">{{cite news |title =Linden Tries to Salvage Something From Lockout|url =http://www.nytimes.com/2005/01/21/sports/hockey/21linden.html?fta=y|author =Lapointe, Joe|publisher =[[New York Times]]|date =[[2005-01-21]]|accessdate =2008-03-13}}</ref> He was named captain of the Canucks at the age of 21, making him one of the youngest captains in league history. While captaining the Canucks, Linden led the team to within a game of winning the [[Stanley Cup]] in [[1994 Stanley Cup Finals|1994]]. In 1998 he was elected President of the [[National Hockey League Players' Association]] (NHLPA), a position he held for eight years.<ref name="Captain of Islanders"/> As President, he played an instrumental role in the [[2004<U+2013>05 NHL lockout]], including taking a direct role in negotiations with league owners.<ref name="Linden Resigns">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/canada/british-columbia/story/2006/07/11/linden-nhlpa.html|title=Linden out as NHLPA president|accessdate=2008-03-01|publisher=CBC|year=2006|author=CBC Sports}}</ref> Off the ice, Linden has taken an active role in charities, and was awarded the [[King Clancy Memorial Trophy]] for leadership on the ice and humanitarian contributions off the ice in [[1996-97 NHL season|1997]].<ref name="King Clancy Trophy">{{cite web|url=http://www.legendsofhockey.net:8080/LegendsOfHockey/jsp/SilverwareTrophyWinner.jsp?tro=KCT&year=1996-97|title=King Clancy Memorial Trophy Winner: Trevor Linden|publisher=''Legends of Hockey''|accessdate=2008-02-18}}</ref>
{{TOClimit|limit=3}}

==Early life==
Trevor Linden's grandfather, Nick van der Linden, immigrated to Canada  from the [[Netherlands]] in 1929.<ref name="Last Time Around">{{cite news |title ='Last time around' for Linden|url =http://www.canada.com/vancouversun/news/sports/story.html?id=9e2101a7-1e3d-49f2-8e91-eb2fbcbd0496&k=88025&p=1|author =MacIntyre, Iain|publisher =[[Vancouver Sun]]|date =[[2008-02-21]]|accessdate =2008-02-21}}</ref> He ran a construction company until his son Lane, Trevor's father, replaced him in 1979.<ref name="Life after hockey">{{cite news |title =Life after hockey|url =http://www.canada.com/vancouversun/news/westcoastnews/story.html?id=0e0d3a19-872c-4dd9-9070-5ff9276da6ed&p=1|author =MacIntyre, Iain|publisher =[[Vancouver Sun]]|date =[[2007-09-01]]|accessdate =2008-03-12}}</ref> Trevor was born in [[Medicine Hat]] to Lane and Edna Linden. Linden was a skilled athlete; despite hockey being his top priority, he also participated in baseball, golf, volleyball, basketball, and speed skating.<ref name="Medicine Hat">{{Cite web|url=http://www.medicinehat.ca/City%20Government/Departments/City%20Clerk/Wall%20of%20Fame/Trevor%20Linden.asp|title=City of Medicine Hat Wall of Fame Biography|accessdate=2008-03-18|publisher=Medicine Hat|year=2008|author=Medicine Hat}}</ref> An excellent student in school, he was offered a scholarship to [[Princeton University]] to play for their hockey team; instead, Linden chose to stay in Medicine Hat and play with the local major junior team, the [[Medicine Hat Tigers]] of the [[Western Hockey League|WHL]].<ref name="Burnside">{{Cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nhl/columns/story?id=1981684|title=Linden to dad: 'Maybe I can make a difference'|accessdate=2008-02-21|publisher=[[ESPN]]|year=2005|author=Burnside, Scott}}</ref> Linden grew up watching the Tigers and idolized [[Lanny McDonald]], who played in Medicine Hat before he joined the NHL.<ref name="Ask A Player">{{Cite web|url=http://canucks.nhl.com/team/app/?service=page&page=NewsPage&articleid=319333|title=Ask A Player - Trevor Linden |accessdate=2008-01-23|publisher=Canucks.com|year=2006|author=Canucks.com}}</ref>

After one season playing with the Medicine Hat Midget Tigers of the [[Alberta Midget Hockey League]] (AMHL), Linden joined the WHL Tigers for the final five games of the [[1985-86 WHL season|1985<U+2013>86 regular season]], where he scored two goals; he also appeared in six playoff games, scoring one goal. The next season, at the age of 16, he made the team full-time. In his first full season in the WHL, Linden had 36 points in 72 games, and then had nine points in 20 playoff games, including two goals in the championship game, helping Medicine Hat win their first [[Memorial Cup]] as Canadian junior champions.<ref name="Local Heroes">{{Citation|last1=Lapp|first1=Richard M.|last2=White|first2=Silas|title=Local Heroes: A History of the Western Hockey League|publisher=Harbour Publishing|location=Madeira Park, BC|year=1993|isbn=1-55017-080-5}}</ref> The next year, Linden had 110 points in 67 games, and captained the Tigers to their second consecutive Memorial Cup title.<ref name="Memorial Cup">{{Cite web|url=http://canucks.nhl.com/team/app/?service=page&page=NewsPage&articleid=322849|title=Not So Junior Experience |accessdate=2008-01-23|publisher=Canucks.com|year=2007|author=Paterson, Jeff}}</ref> During the 1988 WHL playoffs, Linden set a WHL playoff record by scoring the fastest goal from the start of a game, scoring seven seconds into a 6-5 Tigers win over the [[Saskatoon Blades]] on April 15, 1988.<ref name="WHL Record">{{Cite web|url=http://www.whl.ca/records/?id=43|title=WHL Playoff Records|accessdate=2008-01-24|publisher=WHL.ca|year=2003|author=WHL}}</ref> At the [[1988 NHL Entry Draft]], the [[Vancouver Canucks]] selected Linden second overall, after the [[Minnesota North Stars]] selected [[Mike Modano]].<ref name="Recordbook"/>

==NHL career==
[[Image:Trevor Linden draft photo 1988.JPG|left|thumb|200px|Trevor Linden and [[Pat Quinn]] at the [[1988 NHL Entry Draft]], where the Canucks selected Linden 2nd overall]]
===Vancouver Canucks (1988<U+2013>1998)===
Linden made his NHL debut in the [[1988-89 NHL season|1988<U+2013>89 season]], aged 18.<ref name="Salvage Lockout"/> He scored his first goal on [[October 18]], [[1988]], against [[Kelly Hrudey]] of the [[New York Islanders]] and later, on [[November 17]], he scored his first [[hat trick]] against the [[Minnesota North Stars]].<ref name="NHLPA Bio">{{Cite web|url=http://nhlpa.com/WebStats/PlayerBiography.asp?ID=3298|title=NHLPA Player Bio|accessdate=2008-01-23|publisher=NHLPA|year=2008|author=National Hockey League Players Association|authorlink=National Hockey League Players Association}}</ref><ref name="Canucks Hall of Fame">{{Cite web|url=http://canucks.nhl.com/team/app/?service=page&page=NHLPage&bcid=27|title=Canucks Hall of Fame|accessdate=2008-03-01|publisher=Vancouver Canucks|year=2008|author=Vancouver Canucks}}</ref> Linden finished the season tied for the team lead in goals (30) and second for points (59). He was the first Canucks rookie to score 30 goals.<ref name="Local Heroes"/><ref name="2006<U+2013>07 Media Guide">{{cite book | last = Vancouver Canucks | title = 2006<U+2013>07 Vancouver Canucks Media Guide | year = 2006 | publisher = Hemlock Printers Ltd. | location = Vancouver | pages = 264}}</ref>  Linden also became the first rookie to win the [[Cyclone Taylor Award]], given to the Canucks most valuable player.<ref name="2006<U+2013>07 Media Guide"/> He was named to the [[NHL All-Rookie Team]], and finished second to [[Brian Leetch]], of the [[New York Rangers]], in voting for the [[Calder Trophy]], given to the rookie of the year.<ref name="Linden 2.0">{{Cite web|url=http://canucks.nhl.com/team/app/?service=page&page=NewsPage&articleid=322834|title=Linden 2.0|accessdate=2008-03-13|publisher=Vancouver Canucks|year=2007|author=Canucks}}</ref> The Canucks made the playoffs in the [[1988-89_NHL_season#Stanley_Cup_playoffs|1988<U+2013>89 season]], for the first time in three years, and Linden scored seven points in the Canucks' seven-game series loss to the eventual [[Stanley Cup]] champion [[Calgary Flames]].<ref name="Recordbook">{{cite book  | last = National Hockey League  | authorlink = National Hockey League  | title = National Hockey League Official Guide & Record Book 2007  |publisher = Dan Diamond & Associates, Inc.  | date = 2006  | location = Toronto |id = ISBN 978-1-894801-02-7}}</ref>

In his sophomore NHL season, Linden finished second on the team in goals, with 21, and points, 51, and finished third in assists with 30. The following year, he was one of three Canucks to share a rotating captaincy (the others being [[Doug Lidster]] and [[Dan Quinn]]).<ref name="Canuck Legends"/> Linden led the team with 37 assists and 70 points, and made his first appearance in an [[42nd National Hockey League All-Star Game|NHL All-Star Game]]. At the age of 21, he was made sole captain of the team,<ref name="Young Captains">{{Cite web|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/statitudes/news/2000/03/23/lecavalier_youngcaptain/|title=Youth is serving|accessdate=2008-03-18|publisher=CNN/SI|year=2000|author=Hunt, Ryan}}</ref> becoming the youngest Canucks captain.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Fans, peers honour Trevor Linden's 19-year hockey career|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Hockey/NHL/Vancouver/2008/04/07/5213956-cp.html|publisher=The Canadian Press|year=2008|accessdate=2008-04-29}}</ref> That season, Linden led the Canucks in scoring for a second straight year with 75 points (31 goals and 44 assists), leading the Canucks to their first division title since the [[1974-75 NHL season|1974<U+2013>75 season]].<ref name="2006<U+2013>07 Media Guide"/>  They repeated as [[Smythe Division]] champions the following year, setting franchise records for wins and points. For the third straight season, Linden surpassed 30 goals and 70 points, finishing with totals of 33 goals and 72 points.<ref name="Recordbook"/>

[[Image:Lindenmclean1994.jpg|right|thumb|200px|Trevor Linden and [[Kirk McLean]] after the Canucks won game 6 of the [[1994 Stanley Cup Finals]] in Vancouver]]
In the [[1993-94 NHL season|1993<U+2013>94 season]], Linden scored 32 goals, the fifth time in six seasons he had scored at least 30, but his points total fell to 61 as the Canucks finished 10 points behind the division leader. Although they were the seventh seed in the playoffs, the Canucks reached the [[1994 Stanley Cup Finals|Stanley Cup Finals]] for the first time in 12 years and second time in team history. Playing the New York Rangers, Linden went up against Rangers captain [[Mark Messier]] and led the Canucks to a seventh and deciding game. Despite two goals by Linden, the Canucks lost, 3<U+2013>2.<ref name="Fan Guide">{{cite book  | last = MacKinnon | first = John | title = NHL Hockey: The Official Fans' Guide |publisher = Raincoast Books | date = 1996  | location = Vancouver |id = ISBN 1-55192-047-6}}</ref> Linden finished second on the team in playoff scoring, with 12 goals and 25 points.<ref name="2006<U+2013>07 Media Guide"/>

In the [[1995-96 NHL season|1995<U+2013>96 season]], Linden had 33 goals, 47 assists and 80 points, the most he has ever collected in all three statistical categories.<ref name="1997 NHL Yearbook">{{cite book | last = National Hockey League  | title = 1997 NHL Yearbook | year = 1996 | publisher = Worldsport Properties | location = Toronto | pages = 232}}</ref> The following season marked the end of Linden's ironman streak; between [[October 4]], [[1990]] and [[December 3]], [[1996]], he appeared in 482 consecutive games, the longest in the league at the time.<ref name="1998 NHL Yearbook">{{cite book | last = National Hockey League  | title = 1998 NHL Yearbook | year = 1997 | publisher = Worldsport Properties | location = Toronto | pages = 240}}</ref> The streak established a Canucks record (broken in 2007 by [[Brendan Morrison]]).<ref name="Morrison Ironman">{{cite news |title=Morrison's game milestone|url=http://www.canada.com/theprovince/news/sports/story.html?id=858bf4fc-6eb2-4da2-8c4f-e97315fb7191|author=Willes, Ed|publisher=[[The Province]]|date=[[2007-02-23]]|accessdate=2008-05-12}}</ref> In his 49 games that season, he scored nine goals and 31 assists. At the conclusion of the season, the NHL recognized Linden's contributions to the Vancouver community and awarded him the King Clancy Memorial Trophy.<ref name="1998 NHL Yearbook"/> 

At the start of the [[1997<U+2013>98 NHL season|1997<U+2013>98 season]], the Canucks added free agent Mark Messier, a six-time Stanley Cup winner, and coach [[Mike Keenan]], who were, respectively,  captain and coach, of the New York Rangers when they defeated Vancouver in the Stanley Cup finals. Friction developed between Linden and Keenan early in the season.<ref name="Captain Vancouver">{{Cite web|url=http://www.vanmag.com/articles/07apr/Captainvancouver.shtml|title=Captain Vancouver|accessdate=2008-01-29|publisher=Vancouver Magazine|year=2007|author=McKinley, Michael}}</ref>  As the relationship worsened, Keenan claimed that it was evident that Linden would be traded.<ref name="Captain of Islanders">{{cite news|title=Spots of The Times; Here's How A Captain Operates|url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F0DE7DB113AF932A25751C1A96E958260&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=1|author=Vecsey, George|publisher=[[New York Times]]|date=[[1998-12-11]]|accessdate=2008-02-21}}</ref> After a 5-1 loss to the [[St. Louis Blues (hockey)|St. Louis Blues]], Keenan openly blamed Linden for the loss, a moment Linden refers to as his "darkest time".<ref name="Darkest time">{{cite news |title =Linden outlasts 'darkest time' trade from Canucks|url =http://www.canada.com/theprovince/news/sports/story.html?id=8f587dcd-243b-41da-9aeb-accd1d1d46ac|author =Pratt, Dave|publisher =[[The Province]]|date =[[2008-02-05]]|accessdate =2008-02-21}}</ref> Playing in 42 games with the Canucks before the February Olympic break, Linden had seven goals and 21 points.

===New York, Montreal and Washington (1998<U+2013>2001)===
Linden was traded to the [[New York Islanders]] on [[February 6]], [[1998]] for [[Todd Bertuzzi]], [[Bryan McCabe]], and the Islanders' third round choice (used to select [[Jarkko Ruutu]]) in the [[1998 NHL Entry Draft]]. After the conclusion of the Olympics, in which he participated, Linden joined the Islanders and played 25 games with the team.  He scored 10 goals and seven assists for 17 points to finish the season, with a combined 17 goals and 21 assists for 38 points in 67 games. The following year, his first full season in three years, Linden was second on the team with 47 points, and third with 18 goals; however, on [[May 29]], [[1999]], the Islanders traded Linden to the [[Montreal Canadiens]] for a first round draft pick in the [[1999 NHL Entry Draft]] ([[Branislav Mezei]]), for mostly financial reasons.<ref name="Trade to Canadiens">{{cite news |title =Strapped Islanders Trade Linden To Montreal for a Draft Pick|url =http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9906E6DB1530F933A05756C0A96F958260|author =El-Bashir, Tarik|publisher =[[New York Times]]|date =[[1999-05-30]]|accessdate =2008-03-06}}</ref> The thrill of playing in Montreal, the "centre of hockey," was an exciting prospect to Linden after his time spent with the Islanders, where the arena was usually half-filled when he played there.<ref name="2000 NHL Yearbook">{{cite book | last = National Hockey League  | title = 2000 NHL Yearbook | year = 1999 | publisher = Worldsport Properties | location = Toronto | pages = 256}}</ref>

With Montreal, Linden was often injured, and only appeared in 50 games during his first season with the Canadiens, scoring 30 points, while the next year he appeared in 57 games, scoring 33 points. While with the Canadiens, he signed a four-year contract worth $15 million;<ref name="Canuck Legends"/> however, he was traded for the third time in his career, this time to the [[Washington Capitals]], going with [[Dainius Zubrus]], and [[New Jersey Devils|New Jersey's]] 2nd round choice in the [[2001 NHL Entry Draft]] in exchange for [[Richard Zednik]], [[Jan Bulis]], and Washington's 1st round choice in the 2001 Draft ([[Alexander Perezhogin]]). With Washington, Linden reached the playoffs for the first time in four years, in the [[2000-01 NHL season|2000-01 season]].<ref name="Capitals Trade">{{cite news |title=Linden glad to get second shot at Cup|url=http://www.usatoday.com/sports/hockey/cup01/bonus/caps.htm|author=Graves, Gary|publisher=[[USA Today]]|date=2001-04-10|accessdate=2007-11-21}}</ref>

===Return to Vancouver (2001<U+2013>present) ===
[[Image:Trevor Linden 2007a.jpg|right|thumb|250px|Trevor Linden during the pre-game warm-up in November 2007]]
After 28 games, over two seasons, with the Capitals, Linden scored only three goals and four assists. On [[November 10]], [[2001]], the Capitals traded Linden with a second round draft pick in either [[2002 NHL Entry Draft|2002]] or 2003 to the Canucks for their first round pick in 2002 ([[Boyd Gordon]]) and a third round pick in [[2003 NHL Entry Draft|2003]]. He scored 34 points with Vancouver in 64 games, which included his 1,000th regular season game on [[March 26]], [[2002]] against the [[Los Angeles Kings]].<ref name="1000 Games">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/story/2002/10/24/canucksducks021024.html|title=Canucks honour Linden, welcome Ducks|accessdate=2008-05-09|publisher=CBC.ca|year=2002|author=CBC Sports}}</ref> In his first playoff series with Vancouver in six years, he scored a goal and four assists in six games.

The [[2002-03 NHL season|2002-03 season]] was Linden's first full season with the Canucks since [[1996-97 NHL season|1996-97]], though Linden sprained his knee in the season opener and had to miss two weeks.<ref name="Craighead">{{Cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nhl/news/2002/1024/1450790.html|title=Craighead will play for AHL club in Manitoba|accessdate=2008-05-09|publisher=ESPN.com|year=2002|author=Associated Press}}</ref> He returned in time to be honoured for his 1,000th career game, which he achieved the season before. As he did not want to distract the team from the playoff race, Linden asked for the ceremony to be delayed.<ref name="1000 Games honoured">{{Cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nhl/recap?gameId=221024022|title=Kariya's goal in third allows Ducks to earn tie|accessdate=2008-05-09|publisher=ESPN.com|year=2002|author=Associated Press}}</ref> On [[November 25]], [[2002]], against the [[Minnesota Wild]], Linden scored his 263rd goal with the Canucks, breaking former captain [[Stan Smyl]]'s team record for most goals.<ref name="263 goals">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/story/2002/11/25/canucks-wild021125.html|title=Canucks win, Linden sets record|accessdate=2008-05-09|publisher=CBC.ca|year=2002|author=CBC Sports}}</ref> He finished the year with 19 goals and 22 assists for 41 points, his highest goal total in seven seasons, and his highest points total since [[1998-99 NHL season|1998-99]].

The following season, Linden broke several more Canucks records. In a [[February 16]], [[2004]], game against the [[Colorado Avalanche]], he played in his 897th game as a Canuck, passing Smyl.<ref name="897 games">{{Cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nhl/recap?gameId=240216017|title=Cloutier makes 23 saves in victory|accessdate=2008-05-12|publisher=ESPN|year=2004|author=Associated Press}}</ref> On [[March 8]], once again playing the Avalanche, Linden had two points, including his team-record 674th point with the Canucks, a mark also previously held by Smyl.<ref name="Canuck Legends"/> For the first time in five years, he played in all 82 games, recording 36 points. After a year-long break from hockey during the [[2004-05 NHL lockout]], in which he actively participated in new Collective Bargaining Agreement (CBA) negotiations, Linden again appeared in all 82 games during the [[2005-06 NHL season|2005-06 season]], scoring seven goals and 16 points. Linden became the first player to play 1,000 games with the Canucks on [[April 13]], [[2006]] when they faced the [[San Jose Sharks]].<ref name="2006<U+2013>07 Media Guide"/>

{{q|| quote  ="The career he's had, a lot of us watched him when we were younger, and the runs he's had when he first broke in. He's played for so long, and also playing against him, he's a guy that plays hard all the time. He<U+2019>s a leader. He's a guy that's a good, honest, hard player to play against. He<U+2019>s not cheap. We have a lot of respect also for what he's done for us off the ice as a group of players. I'm not sure if it's his last for sure, but if it is, it definitely was an honor to play with him."|align=left |width=40%|source=[[Jarome Iginla]] talking about Linden after an [[April 5]], [[2008]] game, the Canucks regular season finale, and considered to be Linden's final game<ref name="End of An Era?">{{Cite web|url=http://canucks.nhl.com/team/app?articleid=359382&page=NewsPage&service=page|title=End of An Era?|accessdate=2008-04-08|publisher=Canucks.com|year=2008|author=Dhillon, Sunny}}</ref>}}

In the [[2006-07 NHL season|2006-07 season]] opener, on [[October 5]], [[2006]], Linden scored the game winner against the [[Detroit Red Wings]] to become the first Canuck to score 300 goals with the team.<ref name="300 Goals">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nhl.com/nhl/app?date=10%2F05%2F2006&page=Scoreboard&service=page|title=October 5, 2006 Game Recap|accessdate=2008-03-26|publisher=NHL.com|year=2006|author=Associated Press}}</ref> After notching 25 points in 80 games, he helped the Canucks reach the second round of the playoffs. He scored two game-winning goals in the first round, including the series winning goal against the [[Dallas Stars]] in game seven of their first-round matchup, which was Linden's sixth game-seven goal of his playoff career.<ref name="Game 7">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/hockey/stanleycup2007/story/2007/04/23/nhl-stars-canucks.html|title=Linden lifts Canucks over Stars in Game 7|accessdate=2008-05-12|publisher=CBC.ca|year=2007|author=CBC Sports}}</ref> He finished the playoffs with a team-leading seven points in 12 games. This made Linden the Canucks' all-time leader in playoff goals (34), assists (61) and points (95).<ref name="Resigned 2007">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/canada/british-columbia/story/2007/08/21/trevor-linden.html|title=Canucks re-sign Trevor Linden for 1 year|accessdate=2007-11-11|publisher=CBC|year=2007|author=CBC Sports}}</ref>

After taking the summer to decide if he would return for another season, Linden signed a one-year contract with the Canucks in August 2007.<ref name="Resigned 2007"/> The season was not ideal for Linden, who was a healthy scratch 23 times.<ref name="Retirement seems nearly certain">{{cite news |title=Retirement seems nearly certain for Linden|url=http://www.canada.com/vancouversun/news/sports/story.html?id=16c9bf04-9bdf-4be1-b0ad-f247698c0c2b|author=MacIntyre, Iain|publisher=[[Vancouver Sun]]|date=[[2008-04-07]]|accessdate=2008-05-09}}</ref> In the 59 games he played, he scored seven goals and five assists, by far the lowest totals in his career. Against the [[Calgary Flames]] on [[November 8]], [[2007]], he earned his 412th assist with the Canucks, surpassing Smyl, once again.<ref name="412 assists">{{Cite web|url=http://canucks.nhl.com/team/app?articleid=342729&page=NewsPage&service=page|title=Game Saver|accessdate=2008-05-12|publisher=Canucks.com|year=2007|author=Harland, Kyle}}</ref> In the last game of the regular season, a home game against Calgary, Linden was named the first star, skated a lap around [[GM Place]] to a standing ovation and received handshakes from the Calgary players, leading many to believe that he had played his last game.<ref name="Retirement seems nearly certain"/>

==Off the ice==
===Personal===
In 1995, Linden married Cristina Giusti,<ref name="Captain Vancouver"/> who is presently the owner of Basquiat, a Vancouver boutique.<ref name="Fashion Magazine">{{Cite web|url=http://www.fashionmagazine.com/shops/regulararticle/28/|title=Vancouver Style Profile: Cristina Linden|accessdate=2008-01-29|publisher=Fashion Magazine|year=2006|author=Raya, Jessica}}</ref> Linden's younger brother, [[Jamie Linden (ice hockey)|Jamie Linden]], also played ice hockey. After a lengthy junior career in the [[Western Hockey League]] (WHL), Jamie played four games with the [[Florida Panthers]] in the [[1994-95 NHL season|1994<U+2013>95 season]], before finishing his hockey career in the minor leagues. Together with Trevor, Jamie is now a property developer, something they developed an interest in while growing up Medicine Hat.<ref name="Life after hockey"/> Trevor has indicated that after his playing career is finished, he would like to become more involved in real estate.<ref name="Life after hockey"/><ref name="Real Estate">{{cite news |title =Pro athletes make a sport of real estate|url =http://www.theglobeandmail.com/servlet/story/RTGAM.20071026.re-sports-1026/REStory/RealEstate/|author =Gold, Kerry|publisher =[[Globe and Mail]]|date =[[2007-10-26]]|accessdate =2008-03-12}}</ref> Linden is also an avid and competitive cyclist, frequenting the local [[Squamish]] and [[Whistler]] area to mountain bike, in addition to participating in various races.<ref>{{citeweb|last=Smolens|first=Amy|title=An Interview with "Cyclist" Trevor Linden|url=http://www.canadiancyclist.com/dailynews/December/12.19.076.51PM05.shtml|date=2007-12-19|publisher=Canadian Cyclist|accessdate=2008-05-09}}</ref>  Most significantly, in the summer of 2007, Linden competed in the TransAlp bikerace, a 600km race across the European [[Alps]]. Linden and racing teammate John Ramsden finished 48th out of the 122 competing two-man teams over the eight-day competition.<ref name="Biking">{{Cite web|url=http://canucks.nhl.com/team/app/?service=page&page=NewsPage&articleid=337412|title=Mountain training keeps Linden, Gelinas at their peak|accessdate=2008-01-23|publisher=NHL.com|year=2007|author=Raimondi, Jennifer}}</ref>

===NHLPA President===
As a player representative to the [[NHL Players Association]] since 1990,<ref name="Masterton Story">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nhl.com/nhl/app?articleid=358424&page=NewsPage&service=page|title=Linden handles role transition with class |accessdate=2008-03-28|publisher=NHL.com|year=2008|author=Kimelman, Adam}}</ref> Linden was responsible for being the contact between his teammates and the NHLPA.<ref name="Salvage Lockout"/> He saw the experience as a chance to be involved in the business side of the sport.<ref name="Masterton Story"/> In light of this service, Linden was elected President of the NHLPA in June 1998. Consequentially, Linden was actively involved in negotiations with [[Gary Bettman]] and the NHL on a new [[Collective bargaining|CBA]] that ended the [[2004<U+2013>05 NHL lockout|2004<U+2013>05 lockout]].<ref name="Linden Resigns"/> This included a final meeting in January 2005 between Linden and [[Harley Hotchkiss]], the chairman of the NHL Board of Governors, in an attempt to avoid losing the NHL season.<ref name="Salvage Lockout"/> Despite this meeting, a result was not found in time to keep the NHL from cancelling the [[2004-05 NHL season|2004<U+2013>05 season]].

===Attachment to Vancouver===
{{Quote box
 | quote  = If somebody asked me to come up with a mental image of my hockey career, there is absolutely no doubt I would be wearing the uniform of the Vancouver Canucks in it.
 | source = Trevor Linden<ref name="Canuck Legends"/>
 | width  = 35%
 | align  = right
}}
Linden's long tenure with the Canucks, deep attachment to the city of [[Vancouver]] and history of charitable community service and involvement have made him one of the most beloved and respected players among fans in franchise history.<ref name ="Order of BC">{{cite web|title=Order of British Columbia citation for Trevor Linden|url=http://www.protocol.gov.bc.ca/protocol/prgs/obc/2003/2003_TLinden.htm|author=British Columbia|publisher=British Columbia|date=2003|accessdate=2008-03-13}}</ref> His 2001 return to the Canucks was an emotional event for fans and player alike, with Linden admitting that he was too excited to sleep the night before his first game back.<ref name="Canuck Legends"/> He is still often referred to affectionately as 'Captain Canuck', despite not having captained the team since 1997.<ref name="Captain Canuck">{{cite news |title =Linden Letters: Readers tell us why Mr. Canuck should stay or go|url =http://www.canada.com/vancouversun/news/story.html?id=a18129da-831e-4f00-b9f1<U+2013>84f9fd84d381|author =Vancouver Sun|publisher =[[Vancouver Sun]]|date =[[2007-08-17]]|accessdate =2008-03-11}}</ref> On [[April 5]], [[2008]], the Canucks' final game of the [[2007<U+2013>08 NHL season|2007<U+2013>08 season]], the Vancouver crowd gave Linden a standing ovation before the start of the third period. Once the game ended, the crowd again rose to their feet in recognition of Linden.<ref name ="Talk of the Town">{{cite web|title=Talk of the Town|url=http://canucks.nhl.com/team/app/?service=page&page=NewsPage&articleid=359769|author=Jory, Derek|publisher=Canucks.com|date=2008|accessdate=2008-05-06}}</ref> 

In addition to hockey, Linden has also undertaken a considerable amount of charitable work. Working primarily with children, he has made frequent appearances at the [[BC Children's Hospital]] and Canuck Place, a hospital for terminally ill children.<ref>{{citeweb|last=MacQueen|first=Ken|title=Trevor Linden|url=http://www.macleans.ca/article.jsp?content=20040701_83565_83565|publisher=[[Maclean's]]|accessdate=2008-05-09}}</ref> In 1995, he inaugurated the Trevor Linden Foundation to raise money for local charities and also hosts an annual golfing event as a fundraiser for BC Children's Hospital.<ref>{{citeweb|last=Kimelman|first=Adam|title=Linden handles transition role with class|url=http://www.nhl.com/nhl/app?articleid=358424&page=NewsPage&service=page|publisher=NHL.com|year=2008|accessdate=2008-04-21}}</ref> When he was awarded the [[Order of British Columbia]] in 2003, the citation referred to him as a "hockey player and humanitarian".<ref name="Order of BC"/>

==International play==
{{MedalTableTop|}}
{{MedalCountry | {{flagicon|Canada}} [[Canada]] }}
{{MedalSport | Men's [[Ice Hockey]]}}
{{MedalCompetition|[[World Junior Ice Hockey Championships|World Junior Championships]]}}
{{MedalGold | [[World Junior Ice Hockey Championships|1988 Soviet Union]] | Ice Hockey }}
{{MedalCompetition|[[Ice Hockey World Championships|World Championships]]}}
{{MedalSilver | [[1991 Men's World Ice Hockey Championships|1991 Finland]] | Ice Hockey }}
{{MedalCompetition|[[World Cup of Hockey|World Cup]]}}
{{MedalSilver | [[1996 World Cup of Hockey]] | Ice Hockey }}
{{MedalBottom}}
Throughout his hockey career, Linden has appeared in five international tournaments for [[Canada national men's ice hockey team|Team Canada]]. He first appeared on the world stage at the [[World Junior Ice Hockey Championships|1988 World Junior Championships]], a tournament Canada won, where he scored one goal. His first senior international tournament was the [[1991 Men's World Ice Hockey Championships|1991 World Championship]], in which he contributed one goal and four assists in ten games as Canada won the silver medal. Linden was also invited to training camp for the [[1991 Canada Cup]] roster, but was released early.<ref name="Cut from Canada Cup">{{cite news |title =Cuts by Team Canada|url =http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9D0CE7DB123FF932A1575BC0A967958260|author =Associate Press|publisher =[[New York Times]]|date =[[1991-08-21]]|accessdate =2008-03-01}}</ref> In the [[1996 World Cup of Hockey|1996 World Cup]], the successor to the [[Canada Cup]], Linden helped Canada to a second place finish with a goal and an assist over eight games.

Two years later, Linden was selected as a member of Team Canada in the [[1998 Winter Olympics|1998 Nagano Olympics]].<ref name="1998 selection">{{cite news |title =Gretzky In, Messier Out As Canada Picks Team|url =http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9407E5DC1E3AF933A05752C1A961958260|author =Willes, Ed|publisher =[[New York Times]]|date =[[1997-11-30]]|accessdate =2008-03-20}}</ref> Though he injured his knee only weeks before,<ref name ="Olympics">{{cite web|title=Linden's limbo to end soon|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/SlamNaganoHockeyMenArchive/feb2_linden.html|author=Associated Press|publisher=SLAM! Sports|date=1998|accessdate=2007-11-21}}</ref> he played in all six games, scoring one goal, a game-tying marker with 67 seconds left against the [[Czech Republic national ice hockey team|Czech Republic]] that sent the semi-final game to overtime.<ref name ="67 Seconds">{{cite web|title=Olympic Men's Hockey Recap (Czech Republic-Canada)|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/olympics/events/1998/nagano/scoreboards/1998/02/20/recap.czech_republic.canada.html|author=CNN/SI|publisher=Sports Illustrated|date=1998|accessdate=2007-11-21}}</ref> Canada finished fourth in the tournament.<ref name="Recordbook 1999">{{cite book | last = National Hockey League | authorlink = National Hockey League  | title = National Hockey League Official Guide & Record Book 1998<U+2013>99  |publisher = NHL Publishing | date = 1998 | location = Toronto |id = ISBN 0-920445-60-8}}</ref> Later that summer, he participated in the [[1998 Men's World Ice Hockey Championships|1998 World Championships]]. He scored one goal and four assists as Canada finished fifth.<ref name="Legends of Hockey">{{Cite web|url=http://www.legendsofhockey.net:8080/LegendsOfHockey/jsp/SearchPlayer.jsp?player=10949|title=Trevor Linden Page|accessdate=2008-04-22|publisher=Legends of Hockey|year=2007|author=Legends of Hockey}}</ref>

